A composite literal holds one field whose value is a genuinely multi-line
element (a block child forces the author's line break). The element's true
rendered width is unknowable to breakFirstWideLiteral — it reaches gofmt as a
single-rune placeholder (forceMarker) — so a literal packing it onto its brace
line is treated as over budget without measuring, and its fields break.

This is unrelated to the element's OWN layout rule: the element paren-wraps
because it is genuinely multi-line (an author line break inside it), never
because its line was long. A flat element on a long line would not paren-wrap
at all — see breakwide_nav_items, where <UploadDownloadIcon/> and <UsersIcon/>
stay bare on their broken lines despite those lines being the reason the
literal broke.

-- input.gsx --
package ui

var nav = []item{
	{label: "Team View", icon: <UsersIcon>
		<title>users</title>
	</UsersIcon>, page: TeamViewPage{}},
}
-- fmt.golden --
package ui

var nav = []item{
	{
		label: "Team View",
		icon:  (
			<UsersIcon>
				<title>users</title>
			</UsersIcon>
		),
		page:  TeamViewPage{},
	},
}
